segments.text: I just got back from the midnight showing of Saw 5 and I have to review it before I
go to sleep because I'm still excited about it, but I just want to let you guys know that
the first half of this review is going to have no spoilers at all so you don't have
to worry about it being ruined for you, and the second half of this video is going to
have spoilers, but I will warn you beforehand so you can close out of the video, and then
after you see Saw 5 you can come back and watch the spoilers.
Also be very wary of the comments underneath the video, I would suggest that if you haven't
seen Saw 5 you shouldn't go to the comments because people are going to be commenting
about the ending and stuff, so if you haven't seen Saw 5 don't check out the
comments on this video either. So hopefully you got all that, now let's talk about Saw 5.
Now some of you might not know this, but I was extremely excited about Saw 5.
Okay, all of you knew that, obviously. So I was, you know, really hyped up and excited
to see it, and I have to say that it was definitely better than Saw 4, not
exactly what I was expecting, but it was still really really really good and it's
just made me really really excited for Saw 6. Now there were two plots going on
in this movie, one of them was great and the other one was completely irrelevant
as far as I can tell. The great plot was with Hoffman tying up all his loose ends
and stuff, and the irrelevant plot was with five random strangers, kind of like
in Saw 2, who, you know, have to go through these traps and stuff, but I
totally missed how it tied into the movie at all, and I'm pretty sure that's
because it didn't tie into the movie at all, so that was really bizarre and I
didn't care about the characters at all because they weren't, you know,
introduced well really, so it was just really really strange, but luckily
Hoffman's story was really really really awesome and totally made up for that, so
that's okay. Of course, as everyone knows, the tagline of Saw 5 was, you won't
believe how it ends, and I guess that's sort of true because I sure didn't see
the end coming, I'm not gonna spoil it, don't worry, but the end was really, you
know, the Saw movies are known for their big twist endings and stuff, but I
thought that the best part of Saw 5 was the storyline, like in general, everything
leading up to the ending. The ending was not, you know, crazy shocking or anything
like usual, it was not a huge Saw twist moment, so you know, that was a little
surprising, I guess. That's not to say that the ending wasn't good because it
really was, but it was not exactly what I was expecting, and seriously, everything
leading up to the end was better than the ending, which is still good
because the movie was good. Saw 5 left like no closure at all at the end of
the movie, and it pretty much just left the door wide open for Saw 6, which
obviously is already scheduled to come out next year, so you know, we knew it was
coming and everything, but man oh man, it really left the door open, it didn't even,
you know, try to close it at all, like the wind isn't gonna blow it open or
anything, it's just open. But like I said, the plot of Hoffman and everything,
that was really, really awesome, and it fit very well into the Saw series in
my opinion, so congratulations to the writers for that. But I'll smack him
in the face for the other irrelevant plot line, I don't know what the hell
they were thinking. It was pretty much just an excuse to put traps in the
movie because it was literally completely irrelevant. But whatever, like I
said, I love the Hoffman storyline, so you know, I guess it balances out. David
Hackle directed this movie, and it was his first time directing a movie, I think
in general, but definitely his first time directing a Saw movie, and Darren
Bousman had done the Saw movies, directing them from two through four,
and then of course James Wan did the first one, and man David Hackle showed
how bad Darren Bousman was getting when he got to Saw 4, because Saw 4,
like the directing and everything, was really, really bad. It was too fast-paced,
you know, everything was just really bad about that. But the directing in Saw 5
is very much more like Saw 1, in the sense that it's calm, it's
understandable, you know, you can actually figure out what the hell is going on
without researching and watching it like five times, like you had to with
Saw 4. So in that sense, like I said, Saw 5 is definitely a lot better than
Saw 4. And of course, congratulations to David Hackle, because he did an
excellent job. The acting in the Hoffman plot with Hoffman, Strom, Jigsaw,
all of them was fantastic, of course, I don't know, you know, what would you
expect. So that was great, but in the irrelevant plot, all of the women in it,
because there's like two guys and three girls, they were god-awful, like it was
harder to stomach their acting than it was to stomach the gore in Saw 5. And
there really wasn't that much gore in Saw 5 to begin with, it really was
probably the least gory of all the movies, as far as I can tell. But you
know, the gore really wasn't that bad at all, but really honestly, the acting
was like hard to watch. Like I wanted to just look away and be like, God, they suck,
but I had to keep watching. So you know, luckily the two guys that were in it
actually were really, really, really good. So they made up for it, they
balanced out the crappy girls. Visually, the movie was fantastic. Like I said,
David Hackle did a great job with that. And it definitely was one of the
better-looking Saw movies, you know, lighting, just that whole everything. It
just looked a lot better than Saw 4. But the only complaint that I have is
actually a really huge complaint. And it kind of screwed things up a little
bit. Basically, the opening title sequences, you know, like when it says the,
you know, directed by that whole thing, and then it says Saw 5, Saw 4, whatever.
You know, in all the previous movies, it was the nice little almost elegant
and classy sort of, it just says it, you know, like in the letters going
across, it just says Saw 4, Saw 3, whatever. In Saw 5, it was an extremely
cheesy as hell, like really bad title slide. And like it said Saw, and then
all of a sudden like the 5 came in and like slammed into the Saw and like
went behind it. And it just looked really, really lame, like a really cheesy
horror movie. And not even a horror movie, it was like a superhero movie or
something like that, I don't even know, but it was really lame. And luckily,
that doesn't affect the plot or anything like that, so it's not a huge
deal. And I'm just whining about it. But it still was really weird because
now what are they gonna do in Saw 6? If they go back to the old thing,
it just randomly stops in Saw 5 and then goes back to normal. I don't
know. But whatever, like I said, it's really not that important. It's just
something that kind of irritated me at the time. Oh, and another thing that I
have to say that irritated me, this is going back to the acting, was Strom. He
kept like speaking the plot of the movie out loud, like as though it wasn't
understandable, like the writers realized like man, this is not really
understandable, people aren't gonna get it. Let's just have Strom explain it. Like
he literally, he was like talking to himself and like explaining things out
loud. And you know, it was a little bit awkward to see that because it was
like, why is he talking? There's nobody there. I mean, you know, I know they do
that in movies sometimes, but it was just weird. So that was just the only other
thing that kind of irritated me, you know, but still didn't affect the plot. But
all in all, Saw 5 was definitely a great movie. It was definitely a lot better than
Saw 4, like I said. It was maybe just slightly under Saw 3 and you know, which
is good because Saw 3 was fantastic. So it's slightly under Saw 3, I guess, and
it was very good. But most likely, the general public, which is you know, the
majority of people will hate this movie because they don't understand that the
story is still being told and that it's being left open for Saw 6. So they're
gonna think that, you know, like this might be the last movie and they're
gonna say it sucks and all that stuff. But you know, us smart people, all the
people that look into the movie, we know. We know the truth. It'll finish up in
Saw 6. So everything's good, I hope. No, but seriously, hopefully they do tie
everything up in Saw 6 and they have, you know, like a legitimate story and
everything because I think Saw 6 is gonna be the last one to keep dragging
it on would really just ruin the series. So hopefully they stop at Saw 6
and they make it, you know, like a real awesome finish. So that's it for the
non-spoiler part. I'm going to start talking about spoilers from the movie
like the ending and just, you know, stuff that happens. So if you have not
seen Saw 5, please close out of the video right now. Go watch something
else. Go watch Saw 4 again. I don't care. Or go watch Saw 5 and then
come right back here and watch the spoiler section. Whatever you do, if you
haven't seen Saw 5, just close out of the video right now. Okay, by now,
anyone that hasn't seen Saw 5 should be gone. So let's talk about it. And
the reason was for partial nudity. I don't think I fell asleep or anything,
but there was no nudity in Saw 5 anywhere, as far as I can tell. You know,
can someone explain that to me in the comments maybe and tell me where
there was nudity? I totally missed it. Not that I'm saying that I was
hoping for it or anything, but it's just a little bizarre. So yeah, if
you know where the nudity was, let me know because I actually am
interested to find out. Some people are confused of whether or not
Perez is dead, Agent Perez. She is apparently dead, even though they
didn't show her picture when they were showing Detective Matthews
and Rigg and all of them. She's not one of them. She's FBI, so they
wouldn't have showed her picture there. She's not part of them. But
apparently, she did die overnight while they were in the hospital.
And the last two things really that I want to talk about are things
that I think are unexplained at the moment. What was the deal with
the note that was left on Hoffman's desk that said, I know who you
are? Who was that supposed to be from? Strom or Jill? If you
guys, if I missed something, please let me know because I don't
know what the hell happened there. And the second thing is,
they were in a fully furnished version of the Saw II house,
weren't they? Or was I going insane? I know it was late, but I
was fully awake for this whole thing. They were definitely
walking around. And by they, I mean, Erikson and Strom. Yeah,
I think it was Strom. Yeah, Erikson and Strom. They were
walking around in the Saw II house, but it was fully
furnished. And I mean, like, what was that all about? I
have no idea what the hell I was watching there. If that is
also something that's unexplained, then I guess we'll
just have to wait and find out in Saw VI. But I really want to
know. So if you know, let me know. And that's really all I
have to say about Saw V because, you know, there's still
stuff being figured out. But for the most part, I got the
gist of it. It wasn't as confusing as Saw IV was, which
was, you know, thank God because Saw IV was really damn
confusing. And, you know, in the comments, I want you guys
to let me know what you thought of the movie. Be honest,
you know, if you really didn't like it, let me know. If
you really loved it, let me know. And you know, I'll accept
anybody's opinions because I can understand both ways why
people would hate it and why people would like it. So
like I said, let me know in the comments what you
thought, video responses, whatever you want to do. And
for those of you who will probably ask me, I will of
course be doing all of the coverage for Saw VI when it
gets closer next year. All right, I really have to go
get some sleep now. So you know, just comment and
everything, do what you got to do. And that's pretty
much it.
